The group, which owns thousands of Nortel's patents, strengte on Thursday, an avalanche of complaints for patent infringement against mobile phone manufacturers, including Google, the company, the bankruptcy auction of Nortel was outbid by him.
Rockstar, the consortium that bought the Nortel's patents for $4.5 billion, sued Samsung Electronics Co Ltd, HTC Corp, Huawei and four other companies for patent infringement in the U.S. District Court in Texas.
Rock star is located in the community ownership of Apple, Microsoft, BlackBerry, Ericsson and Sony.
Google is accused in seven cases of patent infringement.
The patents affect technology, put on the Internet searches in accordance with relevant advertising, according to the lawsuit, which is the heart of Google's search engine business.
Representatives of Samsung, HTC, Huawei and Rockstar were not immediately reachable.
Samsung, HTC and Huawei produce mobile phones that work with Google's Android operating system, which is in sharp competition on the mobile products from Apple and Microsoft.
In 2011, Google gave an initial bid of $900 million for Nortel's patents.
Google has increased its offer several times and offered $4.4 billion.
After it was outbid on the Nortel patents, Google acquired Motorola Mobility for $12.5 billion, a business that was motivated in part by Motorola's library of patents.
